column16:
What's your home address?
If you are not comfortable of providing the accurate location, you don’t have to give your exact address. Just something nearby is great — like a street corner, the name of a shop, or your building (no unit number needed). Anywhere within 50 meters of your home works!
column17:
Scenario 1.1
Policy Description:
Allow 4–6 story buildings (65 ft max) at the key intersections or transit hubs shown in orange, and lift unit-count limits there. 

Everyday Framing:
In each orange-shaded intersection on the map, you’d see new 4–6 story apartment buildings—some units set aside as affordable housing, ground-floor shops or services, and high-quality, context-sensitive design helping spread new homes and jobs fairly across the city.

column4: Over the past five years, I’ve lived in a few different places around San Francisco. I started out renting a room in a shared apartment in the Mission District, but after about a year, I had to move when the building was sold. I then found a small studio in the Inner Richmond, which worked out well until rent increases made it unaffordable. In 2022, I moved into a shared house with some friends in the Sunset, which helped lower costs and gave me a more stable situation. Throughout these years, changes were mainly due to affordability, lease issues, and trying to find better living conditions within my budget.
